The case involves clear tort liability for battery under the Civil Code, with the defendant’s assault directly causing traumatic cerebral hemorrhage and related injuries (supported by hospital records and the administrative penalty decision). However, the plaintiff’s initiation of activity on long-disputed land without title proof constitutes contributory fault, justifying apportionment of roughly 50 % of the objectively verifiable economic losses.  

Only the following items are recognized at standard rates and after apportionment:  
- reasonable portion of medical expenses directly linked to the trauma (after excluding hypertension management unrelated to the blow);  
- 12-day hospitalization meal allowance at the locally accepted rate;  
- nursing care calculated from the published annual average service-industry wage;  
- modest, evidence-based sums for nutrition, local travel, and copying.  

Non-compensable or discretionary items (full claimed mental-harm solatium, inflated transportation, and unproven extras) are disallowed. The resulting net award after apportionment and permissible deductions equals 3158 yuan. Court costs are separately allocated to the defendant in the usual proportion.

