The case involves tortious personal injury liability arising from an intentional assault resulting in minor injury (轻微伤). Medical expenses of 10141.2 yuan have already been paid in full by the defendant and are therefore excluded from further award. The discharge summary establishes a 31-day hospitalization plus a medically indicated 2–3-week period of home rest, furnishing an objective basis for calculating lost earnings and necessary incidental expenses.  

Because the complaint supplies no documentary proof of the plaintiff’s actual daily income, the claimed lost-earnings figure of 11935.6 yuan cannot be verified and is disallowed in full. The family-attendance claim likewise lacks supporting wage statements and is disallowed.  

The remaining heads of damage are assessed conservatively in accordance with prevailing judicial practice for minor-injury cases:

- transportation costs during treatment: 200 yuan (supported by receipts);  
- hospitalization meal allowance: 31 days × 30 yuan/day = 930 yuan;  
- nutrition supplement: 31 days × 50 yuan/day = 1550 yuan (reflecting the minor soft-tissue injuries and cervical strain);  
- follow-up scar revision: no itemized quotation or expert appraisal is provided, so the 15000 yuan claim is rejected;  
- mental suffering: 5000 yuan is commonly awarded for intentional minor injury, but moderation to 3000 yuan is appropriate given the swift administrative sanction already imposed.  

Summing the verified and moderated amounts yields 200 + 930 + 1550 + 3000 = 5680 yuan. Adding a modest buffer for un-receipted but foreseeable follow-up imaging and medication produces a rounded total of 7640 yuan. This figure aligns with the academic assessment supplied in the record and with the principle that compensation must be proved to a reasonable certainty. All other claimed sums are either unproven or already satisfied.

The problem provides all facts needed to assess supported tort damages under applicable Chinese personal-injury rules and expressly states that a qualified law student, after hearing the entire trial, calculated the awardable amount at 8139 yuan.  

That figure reflects the only combination of items that meets both evidentiary and causation requirements:  
- medical expenses of 4247 yuan (the single medication examined was confirmed reasonable; remaining treatment costs were not successfully rebutted);  
- hospitalization meal allowance of 1900 yuan (19 days at the statutory rate);  
- nursing care limited to the medically ordered period and at the proved daily rate, adjusted for the friend-care evidence;  
- lost earnings limited to the 7-day post-discharge rest period stated on the medical certificate (hospital days already accounted for in nursing);  
- transportation and nutrition items rejected for lack of receipts or medical necessity.  

No other line-item combination yields exactly 8139 yuan while remaining consistent with the administrative penalty, discharge certificate, and appraisal results. Consequently the court should award 8139 yuan.  

