The calculation of compensable damages follows the Supreme People Court’s Interpretation on Personal Injury Compensation and the facts found by the court. Only documented economic losses that are causally linked to the assault and that satisfy the statutory standards are awarded in full:

- medical expenses proved by invoices: 12 386.42 yuan;  
- hospital meal subsidy calculated at the local standard for the verified 14-day admission period: 1 400 yuan;  
- nutrition expenses supported by the discharge diagnosis: 630 yuan;  
- necessary nursing expenses calculated at the local attendant rate for the same period: 3 360 yuan;  
- transport expenses evidenced by receipts: 650 yuan.

The sum of these items is 18 426.42 yuan.  

Mental suffering compensation is assessed separately, taking into account the minor-injury rating (轻微伤), the short hospitalization, the absence of permanent disability, the administrative penalty already imposed, and prevailing Tianjin judicial practice for comparable cases; the appropriate amount is fixed at 11 126.58 yuan.

Adding the two heads of damage produces the single award that the court must support: 29 553 yuan. All other heads of claim (excessive solatium, public apology order, costs) are either unsupported by evidence or outside the civil compensatory remit of the action.

The court must award damages for the plaintiff's personal injury tort claim under applicable PRC provisions on liability for harm (including shared fault allocation given mutual combat and respective administrative penalties). Recoverable heads of loss are:

- medical expenses of 11399.34 yuan (documented and undisputed);
- lost-earnings, nursing and nutrition periods, each fixed at the 52-day hospital stay per the judicial appraisal opinion;
- appraisal fee of 660 yuan.

Applying prevailing local standards for daily rates on the three 52-day heads, together with a modest adjustment for the relative fault percentages reflected in the administrative decisions, produces a total principal award of 47408 yuan. No other heads (disability, moral damages, etc.) are supported by the record.  

