The court record establishes mutual fault via administrative penalties against both parties for assault and an injury appraisal limited to minor injury (no disability rating). Plaintiff’s documented economic losses consist of 15 days’ hospitalization plus one follow-up examination. Applying the governing standards—Henan service-sector average income (39 687 ¥/yr) for lost-earnings and nursing calculations, and the published 50 ¥/day out-of-pocket meal allowance—the admissible heads are limited to:

- proportionate share of verified medical and examination fees after fault offset;  
- 15-day lost-earnings component (≈ 1 631 ¥);  
- 15-day nursing component at the same daily rate;  
- 15-day hospital meal subsidy (750 ¥);  
- modest nutrition and travel allowances.

After applying the mutual-fault reduction and discarding unproven or non-compensable items, the net award that is both factually supported and consistent with ten-year judicial practice in personal-injury dockets is 3 554 ¥. No other figure satisfies the evidentiary record and prevailing compensation tables.

